        <h1>Websites Project Checklist</h1>
        <p><a href="documents/website_checklist.pdf">Download as PDF</a></p>
        
        <ul>
    <li class="main-ul-level1"><a href="usability_planning.aspx" title="planning for usability">Planning</a> - user-centered design process</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level1"><a href="usability_and_usefulness_accessibility.aspx">Accessibility</a> - products and services should be usable by everyone regardless of age, ability or circumstance</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level1"><a href="user_interface_guidelines.aspx">User Experience</a> - subjective measure of a customer's experiences with a service</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level1">User Input</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level1">Testing </li>
    <li class="main-ul-level2"><a href="usability_and_usefulness_resources.aspx#hci">Human-Computer Interaction Component</a> - study, planning, and design of the interaction between people (users) and computers</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level2"><a href="http://info.umkc.edu/wlg/files/2011/03/useful-usability-findings.pdf">Usability Testing</a> (PDF) - evaluate product/service by testing it on users </li>
    <li class="main-ul-level3">Outline the specific goals for that particular product (not sure if all of the goals that you listed at the top of the document will apply to each product)</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level3">Determine the usability testing timeframe</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level3">Determine the target audience for that product and a recruitment plan (there might be multiple target audiences for some of the products like Peoplesoft). How many test subjects are enough for each different type of target audience?</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level2"><a href="usability_and_usefulness_accessibility.aspx">Accessibility Testing Tools</a></li>
    <li class="main-ul-level2">Load Testing - test system under normal and anticipated peak load conditions</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level2">Automated Testing - use software to execute tests on system and compare actual outcomes to predicted outcomes</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level2"><a href="http://web.missouri.edu/~reissingr/2008%20UI%20Guidelines/testing.html">Testing Guidelines - University of Missouri</a></li>
    <li class="main-ul-level1">Communications</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level1"><a href="usability_and_usefulness_resources.aspx#website_search">Search Engines/Keywords</a> - optimizing a website to improve visibility of a website in search results</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level1">Navigation</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level2"><a href="accessibility_guidelines.aspx">Skip navigation</a> - allows users with screen readers to skip navigation links and go directly to main content</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level2"><a href="http://web.missouri.edu/~reissingr/2008%20UI%20Guidelines/accessibility.html#keyboard">Keyboard accessibility</a> - allow users to navigate webpage using keyboard strokes versus mousing</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level1">Content Management Policy</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level2">Web Policy</a></li>
    <li class="main-ul-level3"><a href="http://identity.missouri.edu/websites/web-policies.php" target="_blank">UM-Columbia Web Policy</a></li>
    <li class="main-ul-level3"><a href="http://www.umkc.edu/web-policy/web-policy.asp" target="_blank">UM-Kansas City Web Policy</a></li>
    <li class="main-ul-level3"><a href="http://communications.mst.edu/web/policies/">UM-Missouri S&T Web Policy</a></li>
    <li class="main-ul-level3"><a href="http://www.umsl.edu/technology/weboffice/WebPagePolicy2008.pdf" target="_blank">UM-St. Louis Web Policy</a> (PDF)</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level2"><a href="https://uminfopoint.umsystem.edu/media/sc/UM-System-Styleguide.pdf" target="_blank">UM System Style Guide</a> (PDF) - see Web Communication Standard on page 25</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level1">Maintenance/Upgrade Plan</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level1"><a href="security_guidelines.aspx" target="_blank">Security</a></li>
    <li class="main-ul-level2"><a href="http://infosec.missouri.edu/classification/dc-sys-apps.html" target="_blank">UM-System Information Security requirements</a> - all devices, websites and software applications must comply</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level2">Annual re-scans - Existing web sites should be periodically scanned with a Web Application Vulnerability scan, to ensure continued compliance. You can contact your campus Information Security office for assistance with these scans.</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level2">Incremental testing plan based on site changes</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level2">Newly created web sites, and new web products also need to successfully pass a Web Application Vulnerability scan.</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level1">Assessment</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level2">List internal goals for this particular pilot, implementation or upgrade</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level2">Write goals in a format that is compatible with some form of measurement (for example, this particular upgrade will yield a 40% decrease in the number of user clicks to desired website destination)</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level2">Have an assessment plan written before software implementation or upgrade. Assessment plan should include:</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level3">Defined beginning and end </li>
    <li class="main-ul-level3">Clear definitions of what is being measured and who is measuring it</li>
    <li class="main-ul-level3">A final report with a pre-defined list of outcome measures (as defined in the assessment plan)</li>
  </ul>
            
